This directory contains code to identify affinis-specific proto-genes. 

1. Start by running main_pipeline.sh in the current directory. This will generate some output files that then need to be moved to separate subdirectorie for analysis of separate categories of proto-genes. 

2. SINGLETONS
- Move the files 
allfeature_reads_M_out_gffinfo_TLREADSONLY_analysis_withreads_CODINGORFS_DAFF_SPECIFIC 
and
allfeature_reads_F_out_gffinfo_TLREADSONLY_analysis_withreads_CODINGORFS_DAFF_SPECIFIC
to the SINGLETONS sudirectory. 
- run singleton_pipeline.sh.
This will produce a file
allfeature_reads_F_out_gffinfo_TLREADSONLY_analysis_withreads_CODINGORFS_DAFF_SPECIFIC_SINGLETONSONLYallfeature_reads_M_out_gffinfo_TLREADSONLY_analysis_withreads_CODINGORFS_DAFF_SPECIFIC_SINGLETONSONLY_AGGREGATED_iso_collapsed
(sorry for the long name) 
which contains a list of each encoded singleton PROTEIN (repeating loci that generate multiple encoded PROTEINS, with format: 
column 1: ORF type (all singleton here) 
column 2: melanogaster gene ID of coding fragment
column 3: number of supporting reads
columns 4+: all fragments on transcript. this may exceed 1, even for singletons, but will all be from the same melanogaster protein (e.g. different exons). 
It will also produce a file
SUMMARY_OUTFILE
which contains information on the number of LOCI (aggregating over proto-proteins from the same locus, i.e. isoforms).

3. COMPOSITES
- Move the files
allfeature_reads_M_out_gffinfo_TLREADSONLY_analysis_withreads_CODINGORFS_DAFF_SPECIFIC
and
allfeature_reads_F_out_gffinfo_TLREADSONLY_analysis_withreads_CODINGORFS_DAFF_SPECIFIC
to the COMPOSITES sudirectory.
- run composite_pipeline.sh.
This will produce a file
allfeature_reads_F_out_gffinfo_TLREADSONLY_analysis_withreads_CODINGORFS_DAFF_SPECIFIC_NCCHIMSONLYallfeature_reads_M_out_gffinfo_TLREADSONLY_analysis_withreads_CODINGORFS_DAFF_SPECIFIC_NCCHIMSONLY_AGGREGATED_iso_collapsed
(sorry for the long and confusing name; NCCHIMS here stands for NONCODING CHIMERAS, aka COMPOSITES) 
which contains a list of each encoded composite PROTEIN (repeating loci that generate multiple encoded PROTEINS), with format
column 1: ORF type (all singleton here: this refers to the number of components in the coding ORF, which for composites is just 1, aka a singleton. Confusing naming.)
column 2: melanogaster gene ID of coding fragment
column 3: number of supporting reads
columns 4+: all fragments on transcript. this number will vary, but will always contain at least two different melanogaster proteins. 
It will also produce a file
SUMMARY_OUTFILE
which contains information on the number of LOCI (aggregating over proto-proteins from the same	locus, i.e. isoforms).

4. CHIMERAS 
- Move the files
CHIMERIC_ORF_POSITION_INFO_TL_reads_(M/F).fna_ORIENTED_m_esltrans
TL_reads_(M/F).fna_ORIENTED_m_esltrans
allfeature_reads_(M/F)_out_gffinfo_TLREADSONLY_analysis_withreads
into the CHIMERAS directory. 
- Download all outgroup genomes from NCBI and place them in the CHIMERAS directory. 
- Run chimera_pipeline.sh.
This will produce two output files ending in 
_chimeric_byprot_bylocus_DAFFSPECIFIC
one for each sex, which list the number of encoded chimeric PROTEINS.
NB: I  manually collapsed a chimera that has multiple loci by the definition used here (overlapping sets of fragments), but which are the result of a tandem duplication, such that it was misleading to count
them independently. These will also appear here, so the total will appear much higher than it actually is (The numbers in the manuscript are accurate). 
 However, there are few enough chimeras that manual curation is feasible. 
Also NB: some of these will appear to be in the non-tinkering locus portion of the genome. However, I manually removed these, as they result from a tandem duplication that started at a tinkering locus and 'spilled over.' 
